Part I - Public Bicycle Scheme Analysis¶

by Akpadolu Uche¶

Introduction¶

The bike sharing system also known as public bicycle scheme is a shared transport service that makes bicycle's accessible for short term use by individuals at low to no cost. The dataset contains information on the bicycle stations, bicycle, users information and trip duration around Sanfrancisco bay area.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset contains 183412 rows and 16columns. it contains information on users including the user gender, membership type, year of birth and use for all trip. It also contains information on the bike stations, both start and end stations which includes their name, latitude and longitude. station_id and bike_id are specific for each station and bike.

There are both quantitative and qualitative variable types:

latitude, longitude variables(continious numeric datatype);
ids,names,birth year, gender(qualitative datatype);
start and end time, duration sec(interval numeric datatype)

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

  1. duration_min

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

  1. member_age
  1. duration_type
  2. gender
  3. start_day
  4. start_hour
  5. user_type

# create function to plot univariant plots

def univariant_plot(plottype, columnname):
    plt.figure(figsize=(5,3))
    name = (columnname)
    plt.title(f'trip distribution over {name}')
    if 'pie' in str(plottype):
        column = bike_share[columnname].value_counts()
        label = column.index
        my_color = sb.color_palette('pastel')
        def func(pct):
            return '{:1.1f}%'.format(pct)
        plottype(data=bike_share, x=column, colors=my_color, labels=label, counterclock=False, startangle=90, autopct=lambda pct: func(pct), normalize=True, explode = (0,0.05,0.05));
        plt.axis('square')
    elif 'hist' in str(plottype):
        my_bin=input('binsize')
        colour = sb.color_palette()[-1]
        plottype(data = bike_share, x = columnname, color = colour, bins = int(my_bin) )
        plt.xlabel(name)
        plt.ylabel('Count')
    else:
        colour = sb.color_palette()[-1]
        a = bike_share[columnname].value_counts(normalize=True)
        b = a.index
        c = a.values
        plottype(data = bike_share, x = b, y = c, color = colour);
        plt.xticks(rotation=90)
        plt.xlabel(name)
        plt.ylabel('Proportion')

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The age column and duration_min column had outliers. The outliers were removed from the dataset.

The start_time and end_time column was splited to seperate date and time. More number of trip was taken at certain hours of the day and days of the week.

9 out of the top ten(10) start and end station are the same. This points that major trips were made along these stations.

Males made up 70% of users in the dataset. Barplot was used to get the distribution by proportion

def bivariant_plot(plottype, column1, column2):
    plt.figure(figsize=(6,4))
    name = column1
    name2 = column2
    plt.title(f'{name} against {name2}')
    
    if 'reg' in str(plottype):
        bike_share_samp = bike_share.sample(n=10000, replace=False)
        my_color = sb.color_palette()[4]
        trans = input('transparency scale')
        jitters = input('jitters')
        plottype(data = bike_share_samp, x=column1, y=column2, scatter_kws={'alpha':float(trans)}, x_jitter= float(jitters))
        plt.axis('square')
    elif 'count' in str(plottype):
        plottype(data = bike_share, x = column1, hue = column2)
    else:
        colour = sb.color_palette()[-1]
        plottype(data = bike_share, x = column1, y = column2, color = colour);
        plt.xticks(rotation=30)

  1. Age had some effect on the duration of trips
  2. start_hour had no influence on duration_type

Interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

  1. Pattern of use at start_hour and start_day across all genders were same
  1. More of the aged bike users are Males
  2. Tuesday and Thursday has higest number of users across max start_hour use (7-9)am and (4-6)pm respectively
